[start section id="20103"]

I have been asked by Dr. Grassi's service to visit with Mr. Benefield for post-operative education purposes.  Briefly, Mr. Benefield is a very pleasant 81-year-old male with a past medical history significant for resected rectal cancer (s/p LAR and post-operative chemoradiation in 1999),  Stage II chronic kidney insufficiency (baseline creatinine 1.9), and colitis.
1.  October 5, 2010, colonoscopy performed after patient presented with hematochezia, showing partial obstructin mass in the sigmoid, approximately 5-cm, biopsy confirmed adenocarcinoma.
2.  October 18, 2010, CT abd/pelvis (non-contrast, due to renal dysfunction) done, no evidence of metastatic disease.
3.  Nonmember 3, 2010, referred to the Uncas on Thames Medical Clinic clinic, underwent repeat colonoscopy showing a circumferential mass at 28 cm from the anal verge.  CEA 1.4.  Abdominal ultrasound negative for disease.
4.  Taken by Dr. Grassi for a low-anterior resection, no evidence of distant disease.  Surgical pathology showing a grade 3 (of 4) adenocarcinoma, invading through the muscularis propria, thirteen regional lymph nodes negative for disease.  Stage at a T3N0, resected Stage II colon cancer.
Mr. Benefield is currently up sitting in bed during our consultation today.

